<p>The <b>Codex Alimentarius</b> (Latin for "food code" or "food book") is a collection of internationally recognized standards, codes of practice, guidelines and other recommendations relating to <a href="/wiki/Food" title="Food">foods</a>, food production and <a href="/wiki/Food_safety" title="Food safety">food safety</a>. Its name derives from the <a href="/wiki/Codex_Alimentarius_Austriacus" title="Codex Alimentarius Austriacus">Codex Alimentarius Austriacus</a>.<sup id="cite_ref-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> Its texts are developed and maintained by the Codex Alimentarius Commission, a body that was established in 1963 by the <a href="/wiki/Food_and_Agriculture_Organization" title="Food and Agriculture Organization">Food and Agriculture Organization</a> of the <a href="/wiki/United_Nations" title="United Nations">United Nations</a> (FAO) and the <a href="/wiki/World_Health_Organization" title="World Health Organization">World Health Organization</a> (WHO). The Commission's main aims are stated as being to <a href="/wiki/Consumer_protection" title="Consumer protection">protect the health of consumers</a> and ensure fair practices in the international food trade. The Codex Alimentarius is recognized by the <a href="/wiki/World_Trade_Organization" title="World Trade Organization">World Trade Organization</a> as an international reference point for the resolution of <a href="/wiki/Dispute" title="Dispute" class="mw-redirect">disputes</a> concerning food safety and consumer protection.<sup id="cite_ref-wto.org_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-wto.org-1" title=""><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2" title=""><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></p>
